\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
\noindent
This document provides a rigorous, bottom-up exploration of document-oriented database management systems (DoDBMS) for computer science students with a strong foundation in relational databases (Microsoft SQL Server, PostgreSQL). We examine the theoretical foundations, data models, storage formats (JSON/BSON), query languages, consistency models, distributed architectures, data modeling patterns, migration strategies, and production operational concerns that define the document paradigm. Rather than treating document databases as ``JSON stores,'' we analyze them as first-class database systems with distinct theoretical underpinnings, trade-offs, and optimization strategies. The document includes 25+ visual diagrams, extensive code comparisons, formal definitions, and practical exercises.
\end{abstract}

\tableofcontents
\newpage

%============================================================================
\section{Introduction: Why Document Databases?}
%============================================================================

\subsection{The Relational Foundation}

In relational database management systems (RDBMS), data integrity is enforced through a strict set of principles that you, as a CS student, have likely internalized:

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Schema rigidity}: Tables must be defined before data insertion (\texttt{CREATE TABLE}). Altering schemas requires \texttt{ALTER TABLE} operations that can lock tables and require downtime.
    \item \textbf{Normalization}: Data is decomposed to eliminate redundancy (1NF, 2NF, 3NF, BCNF, 4NF, 5NF). This is the mathematical bedrock of relational design.
    \item \textbf{Referential integrity}: Foreign keys enforce relationships at the storage engine level via constraint checking.
    \item \textbf{Set-theoretic algebra}: SQL is grounded in relational algebra ($\sigma$ selection, $\pi$ projection, $\bowtie$ join, $\cup$ union, $-$ difference, $\rho$ rename).
    \item \textbf{ACID transactions}: Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability guaranteed at the statement or transaction level.
\end{itemize}

Your mental model is likely:
\begin{equation}
\text{Database} \supset \text{Schema} \supset \text{Table} \supset \text{Row} \supset \text{Column}
\end{equation}

\subsection{The Rise of NoSQL}

The term ``NoSQL'' originated as a Twitter hashtag in 2009 and has since evolved to mean ``Not Only SQL.'' The NoSQL movement was driven by several forces:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Scale}: Internet-scale applications (Google, Amazon, Facebook) needed to handle petabytes of data across thousands of servers.
    \item \textbf{Schema flexibility}: Agile development practices demanded the ability to evolve data models without costly schema migrations.
    \item \textbf{Developer productivity}: Object-relational impedance mismatch caused friction between OOP code and flat relational tables.
    \item \textbf{Specialized access patterns}: Different workloads (graphs, time-series, key-value, documents) needed specialized storage engines.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The Document Inversion}

Document databases invert several relational assumptions:

\begin{definition}
A \textbf{document database} is a type of NoSQL database designed to store, retrieve, and manage \textbf{semi-structured data} in the form of documents. Documents are self-describing, hierarchical data structures that do not require a predefined global schema. Each document is an atomic unit of consistency.
\end{definition}

The mental model becomes:
\begin{equation}
\text{Database} \supset \text{Collection} \supset \text{Document} \supset \text{Field} \supset \text{Value (possibly nested)}
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{01_mental_model.png}
\caption{Mental model comparison: Relational (left) vs Document (right). Notice how the document model allows arbitrary nesting, while the relational model enforces flat rows.}
\label{fig:mental-model}
\end{figure}

\begin{rdbmsnote}
Think of a \textbf{collection} as a table, but one where every row can have different columns. Think of a \textbf{document} as a row, but that row can contain entire sub-tables (arrays of sub-documents) within it. The foreign key relationship becomes either an embedded sub-document or a reference (\texttt{\$lookup}).
\end{rdbmsnote}

\subsection{The CAP Theorem Context}

Document databases typically emerge in the context of distributed systems where the CAP theorem applies:

\begin{definition}
In a distributed data store, it is \textbf{impossible} to simultaneously guarantee all three of:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Consistency} ($C$): Every read receives the most recent write or an error.
    \item \textbf{Availability} ($A$): Every request receives a non-error response (without guarantee it contains the most recent write).
    \item \textbf{Partition Tolerance} ($P$): The system continues to operate despite arbitrary message loss or network partitions.
\end{itemize}
A distributed system can satisfy at most two of these three guarantees.
\end{definition}

Traditional single-node RDBMS choose CP (Consistency + Partition tolerance, since partitions are handled by failing). Distributed document databases often choose \textbf{AP} (Availability + Partition tolerance) with \textbf{eventual consistency}, though modern systems offer tunable consistency per operation.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{07_cap_theorem.png}
\caption{The CAP Theorem triangle. MongoDB defaults to AP but can be tuned to CP with majority read/write concerns.}
\label{fig:cap}
\end{figure}

%============================================================================
\section{The Document Data Model in Depth}
%============================================================================

\subsection{What Is a Document?}

A document is a self-contained record that encapsulates both data \textit{and} schema. Unlike a relational row, which derives meaning from its table definition, a document carries its own structure.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=json, caption={A MongoDB-style Document Representing a Book}, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
{
    "_id": ObjectId("507f1f77bcf86cd799439011"),
    "title": "Deep Learning for Computer Vision",
    "authors": [
        { "name": "Ian Goodfellow", "affiliation": "Google" },
        { "name": "Yoshua Bengio", "affiliation": "U. Montreal" }
    ],
    "metadata": {
        "pages": 775,
        "publisher": "MIT Press",
        "isbn": "978-0262035613"
    },
    "tags": ["AI", "deep learning", "CNN"],
    "published": ISODate("2016-11-18T00:00:00Z"),
    "available": true,
    "borrow_count": 142,
    "reviews": [
        { "user": "alice", "rating": 5, "text": "Excellent!" },
        { "user": "bob", "rating": 4, "text": "Very thorough" }
    ]
}
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{keyinsight}
The document above contains:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Scalar values: \texttt{title} (String), \texttt{available} (Boolean), \texttt{borrow\_count} (Int)
    \item Arrays: \texttt{tags} (Array of Strings)
    \item Arrays of sub-documents: \texttt{authors}, \texttt{reviews}
    \item Nested documents: \texttt{metadata}
    \item Special types: \texttt{ObjectId}, \texttt{ISODate}
\end{itemize}
In RDBMS, representing this requires at least four tables (books, authors, metadata, reviews) with foreign keys and JOIN operations. In a document database, it is \textbf{atomic} at the document level.
\end{keyinsight}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{11_document_example.png}
\caption{Visual breakdown of a document's structure. The \texttt{address} sub-document is analogous to an embedded foreign table.}
\label{fig:document-example}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Collections: Schema-Flexible, Not Schema-Free}

A \textbf{collection} is a grouping of documents. Unlike tables:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item Documents in a collection need not share the same fields.
    \item Field types can vary across documents.
    \item There is no enforced schema at the storage level (though application-level validation is common and recommended).
\end{enumerate}

However, collections are \textbf{schema-flexible}, not schema-free. Applications impose implicit schemas through their query patterns. If your application queries \texttt{db.users.find(\{email: ...\})}, then every document that represents a user \textit{should} have an \texttt{email} field, or the query will silently miss it.

\begin{warning}
Schema flexibility is a \textbf{feature}, not an excuse for chaos. Production applications should use JSON Schema validation (MongoDB 3.6+) or application-level schema enforcement to prevent data corruption.
\end{warning}

\subsection{The Object-Document Impedance Mismatch (or Lack Thereof)}

Relational databases suffer from the ``impedance mismatch'':
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Object-oriented code uses inheritance, composition, and nested objects.
    \item RDBMS uses flat tables, requiring ORMs (Hibernate, SQLAlchemy, Entity Framework) to map between paradigms.
    \item This mapping is lossy and performance-expensive (N+1 query problem).
\end{itemize}

Document databases align naturally with object-oriented and functional programming models because:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item JSON maps directly to dictionaries/maps (\texttt{dict} in Python, \texttt{Map} in Java, \texttt{object} in JavaScript).
    \item Arrays map to lists/arrays.
    \item Sub-documents map to nested objects.
    \item No ORM is needed---the driver returns native data structures.
\end{itemize}

\begin{tip}
In Node.js with MongoDB, \texttt{db.users.findOne()} returns a plain JavaScript object. In Python with PyMongo, it returns a \texttt{dict}. In Java with the MongoDB driver, it returns a \texttt{Document} (which implements \texttt{Map<String, Object>}). The mapping is trivial and lossless.
\end{tip}

%============================================================================
\section{JSON and BSON: The Serialization Formats}
%============================================================================

\subsection{JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)}

JSON is the \textit{lingua franca} of document databases. It is a text-based, human-readable format specified in RFC 8259.

\subsubsection{Formal Grammar}

JSON consists of:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Objects}: Unordered sets of key-value pairs $\{k_1: v_1, \dots, k_n: v_n\}$
    \item \textbf{Arrays}: Ordered sequences of values $[v_1, \dots, v_n]$
    \item \textbf{Values}: Strings, numbers, booleans (\texttt{true}/\texttt{false}), \texttt{null}, objects, or arrays
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Type System Limitations}

JSON's type system is impoverished compared to PostgreSQL:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{JSON Type} & \textbf{PostgreSQL Equivalent} & \textbf{Limitation} \\
\midrule
Number & \texttt{INTEGER}, \texttt{REAL}, \texttt{NUMERIC} & No distinction between int/float \\
String & \texttt{VARCHAR}, \texttt{TEXT} & No length constraints \\
Boolean & \texttt{BOOLEAN} & --- \\
Null & \texttt{NULL} & Semantically ambiguous (missing vs. explicitly null) \\
Array & Arrays (since 9.x) & Homogeneous vs heterogeneous \\
Object & \texttt{JSONB}, \texttt{HSTORE} & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{rdbmsnote}
JSON has no native \textbf{date} type. Dates are serialized as ISO 8601 strings (e.g., \texttt{"2024-01-15T10:30:00Z"}), requiring application-level parsing. There is no \textbf{binary} data type---Base64 encoding is required, inflating size by $\sim$33\%. There is no \texttt{undefined} distinct from \texttt{null}.
\end{rdbmsnote}

\subsection{BSON (Binary JSON)}

BSON is the binary serialization format used by MongoDB and others. It extends JSON with additional types and efficiency optimizations.

\begin{definition}
BSON is a \textbf{binary-encoded serialization} of JSON-like documents. It is designed to be \textbf{traversable} (fast in-place scanning) and \textbf{efficient} (compact encoding of common types). The specification is available at \url{bsonspec.org}.
\end{definition}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{02_json_vs_bson.png}
\caption{JSON (text-based, limited types) vs BSON (binary, rich types, fast traversal).}
\label{fig:json-bson}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Key Extensions Over JSON}

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{ObjectId}: A 12-byte identifier (4-byte timestamp + 3-byte machine ID + 2-byte process ID + 3-byte counter) serving as the default primary key.
    \item \textbf{Date}: 64-bit signed integer representing milliseconds since Unix epoch.
    \item \textbf{Binary}: Raw binary data with a subtype annotation (e.g., generic binary, UUID, MD5).
    \item \textbf{Regex}: Regular expression patterns with options (e.g., \texttt{/pattern/i}).
    \item \textbf{Decimal128}: IEEE 754-2008 128-bit decimal floating point for financial precision.
    \item \textbf{Int32 / Int64}: Explicit integer types (\texttt{NumberInt}, \texttt{NumberLong}).
    \item \textbf{Timestamp}: Internal MongoDB use (operation timestamps, not wall-clock time).
    \item \textbf{MinKey / MaxKey}: Special comparison values.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{24_bson_types.png}
\caption{BSON adds 8+ types that JSON cannot natively express.}
\label{fig:bson-types}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Structure and Traversability}

BSON documents begin with a 32-bit integer indicating total document size. Each element is encoded as:
\begin{equation}
\text{[1-byte type code]} \quad \text{[C-string field name]} \quad \text{[value]}
\end{equation}

This allows the database engine to \textbf{skip} fields without parsing them---critical for fast projection operations (\texttt{SELECT col1, col2} equivalents). The type code acts as a discriminator, telling the parser exactly how many bytes the value occupies.

\subsubsection{Space Efficiency Trade-offs}

BSON is often \textit{larger} than JSON for text data due to:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Field names stored in every document (no schema to factor them out).
    \item Length prefixes on every element and document.
    \item Padding for alignment.
\end{itemize}

However, for numeric arrays and binary data, BSON is significantly more compact. The 16MB document size limit in MongoDB exists partly because BSON documents must be contiguous in memory.

\begin{keyinsight}
BSON's design prioritizes \textbf{read performance} and \textbf{type richness} over minimal storage footprint. This is a fundamental trade-off: RDBMS row formats (e.g., PostgreSQL's heap tuples) factor out metadata via the system catalog; BSON inlines metadata for schema flexibility.
\end{keyinsight}

\subsubsection{ObjectId Deep Dive}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{08_objectid_structure.png}
\caption{The 12-byte ObjectId structure. The first 4 bytes encode a timestamp, making ObjectIds roughly sortable by creation time.}
\label{fig:objectid}
\end{figure}

\begin{tip}
Because ObjectIds embed a timestamp, sorting by \texttt{\_id} is approximately equivalent to sorting by insertion time. This is useful for time-based queries without a separate timestamp index. However, \textbf{never use ObjectId as a shard key}---the monotonically increasing nature causes write hotspots on the last chunk.
\end{tip}

\subsection{Other Formats}

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{MessagePack}: Compact binary format, used by Redis and others. More compact than BSON but fewer types.
    \item \textbf{CBOR} (Concise Binary Object Representation, RFC 7049): Designed for IoT/constrained devices. Self-describing and extensible.
    \item \textbf{UBJSON}: Universal Binary JSON, simpler than BSON but less type-rich.
    \item \textbf{ION}: Amazon's richly-typed, self-describing format used by QLDB.
\end{itemize}

%============================================================================
\section{Data Modeling: Rethinking Normalization}
%============================================================================

\subsection{The Normalization Orthodoxy}

In RDBMS, you normalize to:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item Eliminate insertion, update, and deletion anomalies.
    \item Minimize storage redundancy.
    \item Enforce referential integrity declaratively.
    \item Ensure logical data independence from physical storage.
\end{enumerate}

The normal forms build on each other:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{1NF}: Atomic values, no repeating groups.
    \item \textbf{2NF}: 1NF + no partial dependencies.
    \item \textbf{3NF}: 2NF + no transitive dependencies.
    \item \textbf{BCNF}: 3NF + every determinant is a candidate key.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The Document Denormalization Strategy}

Document databases \textbf{embrace controlled redundancy} to optimize read performance and data locality. This is not abandonment of normalization principles---it is a \textbf{deliberate trade-off} based on access patterns.

\subsubsection{Embedding vs. Referencing}

The fundamental modeling decision in document databases is whether to embed related data or reference it:

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{03_embedding_vs_referencing.png}
\caption{Embedding (left) stores related data in one document. Referencing (right) stores it separately and links via foreign key-like references.}
\label{fig:embed-ref}
\end{figure}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{0.45\textwidth}p{0.45\textwidth}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Embedding (Denormalization)} & \textbf{Referencing (Normalization)} \\
\midrule
Store related data in a single document & Store related data in separate documents \\
Single read retrieves all data & Requires application-level joins or \texttt{\$lookup} \\
Atomic updates within document & Multi-document transactions needed for consistency \\
Risk of data duplication & Risk of query-time overhead \\
Bounded by 16MB document limit & No document size limit on relationship \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsubsection{The ``Building Together'' Rule}

\begin{keyinsight}
\textbf{Embed} when:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item The embedded data is read \textbf{together} with the parent (data locality principle).
    \item The embedded data does not grow unbounded (16MB document limit in MongoDB).
    \item The embedded data is not updated independently across many parents.
    \item The relationship is one-to-few (e.g., a user has 2-3 addresses).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Reference} when:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item The data is updated frequently and shared across many documents.
    \item The relationship is many-to-many.
    \item The embedded array would grow beyond practical limits (e.g., a product with millions of reviews).
    \item The embedded data is large and rarely accessed with the parent.
\end{itemize}
\end{keyinsight}

\subsection{Modeling Patterns}

Document database practitioners have cataloged several reusable patterns:

\subsubsection{The Subset Pattern}

Store the most frequently accessed subset of a large document inline, with a reference to the full document. This is analogous to a covering index but at the document level.

\subsubsection{The Extended Reference Pattern}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{21_extended_reference.png}
\caption{Extended Reference Pattern: Duplicate a small, stable subset of frequently-joined data to avoid \$lookup operations.}
\label{fig:extended-ref}
\end{figure}

Duplicate a small, stable subset of frequently-joined data (e.g., user name and avatar URL) into documents that reference that user, avoiding joins for read-heavy operations. The trade-off is that updates to the referenced data must propagate to all duplicates.

\subsubsection{The Schema Versioning Pattern}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{13_schema_versioning.png}
\caption{Schema Versioning Pattern: Documents with different schema versions coexist in the same collection.}
\label{fig:schema-versioning}
\end{figure}

Add a \texttt{schema\_version} field to documents to allow application-level handling of schema evolution without migration downtime. This is particularly valuable in zero-downtime deployments.

\subsubsection{The Bucket Pattern}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
% \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{12_bucket_pattern.png}
\caption{Bucket Pattern: Group time-series measurements into buckets (e.g., one document per hour) rather than one document per measurement.}
\label{fig:bucket}
\end{figure}

For time-series data, group measurements into ``buckets'' (e.g., one document per hour) rather than one document per measurement. This:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Reduces index size (fewer index entries).
    \item Improves write throughput (fewer index updates).
    \item Improves data locality for range queries.
\end{itemize}

MongoDB 5.0+ formalized this with native \textbf{time-series collections} that automatically apply bucketing.

\subsubsection{The Polymorphic Pattern}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{20_polymorphic_pattern.png}
\caption{Polymorphic Pattern: Different entity types stored in the same collection, distinguished by a type discriminator.}
\label{fig:polymorphic}
\end{figure}

Store different entity types in the same collection, distinguished by a type discriminator field (e.g., \texttt{type: "book"} vs \texttt{type: "electronics"}). This mirrors object-oriented inheritance and avoids sparse tables (where many columns are NULL for most rows).

\begin{tip}
In PostgreSQL, sparse tables waste storage because NULL values still consume a bitmap. In MongoDB, documents simply don't store missing fields---there is no storage penalty for absent fields.
\end{tip}

\subsubsection{The Outlier Pattern}

For data with a long-tail distribution (e.g., most users have 10 followers, but celebrities have millions), store the common case inline and move outliers to a separate collection. This prevents the 16MB document limit from being breached by edge cases.

%============================================================================
\section{Query Languages and Operators}
%============================================================================

\subsection{From SQL to Document Query Languages}

Document databases do not use SQL (though some offer SQL-like interfaces). Instead, they use structured query documents. The query itself is a document that specifies the selection criteria.

\subsubsection{MongoDB Query API}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
% \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{12_sql_vs_mongodb.png}
\caption{Side-by-side SQL vs MongoDB query comparison for all CRUD operations.}
\label{fig:sql-mongo}
\end{figure}

% \begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, caption={SQL vs MongoDB Query Comparison}]
\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, caption={SQL vs MongoDB Query Comparison}, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
// SQL: SELECT * FROM users WHERE age > 21 AND city = 'NYC'
db.users.find({
    age: { $gt: 21 },
    city: "NYC"
})

// SQL: SELECT name, email FROM users WHERE age > 21
//      ORDER BY age DESC LIMIT 10 OFFSET 20
db.users.find(
    { age: { $gt: 21 } },
    { name: 1, email: 1, _id: 0 }
).sort({ age: -1 }).skip(20).limit(10)

// SQL: SELECT city, COUNT(*) FROM users GROUP BY city
//      HAVING COUNT(*) > 5
// MongoDB Aggregation:
db.users.aggregate([
    { $group: { _id: "$city", count: { $sum: 1 } } },
    { $match: { count: { $gt: 5 } } }
])
\end{lstlisting}

\subsubsection{Query Operators Taxonomy}

MongoDB operators follow a consistent naming convention:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llp{7cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Category} & \textbf{Operators} & \textbf{Description} \\
\midrule
Comparison & \texttt{\$eq}, \texttt{\$ne}, \texttt{\$gt}, \texttt{\$gte}, \texttt{\$lt}, \texttt{\$lte}, \texttt{\$in}, \texttt{\$nin} & Scalar comparisons \\
Logical & \texttt{\$and}, \texttt{\$or}, \texttt{\$not}, \texttt{\$nor} & Boolean composition \\
Element & \texttt{\$exists}, \texttt{\$type} & Field metadata queries \\
Evaluation & \texttt{\$regex}, \texttt{\$text}, \texttt{\$where} & Pattern matching and expression evaluation \\
Array & \texttt{\$all}, \texttt{\$elemMatch}, \texttt{\$size} & Array-specific queries \\
Geospatial & \texttt{\$near}, \texttt{\$geoWithin}, \texttt{\$geoIntersects} & Location-based queries \\
Bitwise & \texttt{\$bitsAllSet}, \texttt{\$bitsAnySet} & Low-level bit operations \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsubsection{Array Query Operators}

Arrays are first-class citizens in document databases:

% \begin{lst\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$, literate={$}{{}{{\textdollar}}\1textdollar}}1]
\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
// Find users with ALL specified tags
db.users.find({ tags: { $all: ["premium", "beta"] } })
// Find users where at least one array element matches
db.users.find({ scores: { $elemMatch: { $gt: 80, $lt: 90 } } })

// Find users with exactly 3 tags
db.users.find({ tags: { $size: 3 } })

// Find users with tags array containing "AI"
db.users.find({ tags: "AI" })  // shorthand for $elemMatch
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{rdbmsnote}
In PostgreSQL, array queries require the \texttt{ANY} or \texttt{ALL} operators: \texttt{WHERE 'AI' = ANY(tags)}. MongoDB's array query syntax is more concise because arrays are native to the document model, not an extension type.
\end{rdbmsnote}

\subsection{The Aggregation Pipeline}

MongoDB's aggregation framework is a \textbf{data processing pipeline} modeled after Unix pipes. Each stage transforms the document stream.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{04_aggregation_pipeline.png}
\caption{The aggregation pipeline: documents flow through stages like Unix pipes. Each stage transforms the stream.}
\label{fig:pipeline}
\end{figure}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, caption={Aggregation Pipeline Example},  literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
db.orders.aggregate([
    // Stage 1: Match (filter) - like WHERE
    { $match: { status: "shipped", year: 2024 } },

    // Stage 2: Lookup (left outer join)
    { $lookup: {
        from: "customers",
        localField: "customerId",
        foreignField: "_id",
        as: "customer"
    }},

    // Stage 3: Unwind (flatten array)
    { $unwind: "$customer" },

    // Stage 4: Group (aggregation)
    { $group: {
        _id: "$customer.region",
        totalRevenue: { $sum: "$amount" },
        avgOrder: { $avg: "$amount" },
        orderCount: { $sum: 1 }
    }},

    // Stage 5: Sort
    { $sort: { totalRevenue: -1 } },

    // Stage 6: Project (reshape output)
    { $project: {
        region: "$_id",
        totalRevenue: 1,
        avgOrder: { $round: ["$avgOrder", 2] },
        orderCount: 1,
        _id: 0
    }}
])
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{rdbmsnote}
The aggregation pipeline is MongoDB's answer to SQL's \texttt{SELECT ... FROM ... JOIN ... WHERE ... GROUP BY ... HAVING ... ORDER BY}. However, because stages are ordered and stateful, you must consider \textbf{pipeline optimization}: placing \texttt{\$match} early reduces document flow to subsequent stages, just as predicate pushdown works in query planners.
\end{rdbmsnote}

\subsubsection{Pipeline Optimization Rules}

MongoDB's query optimizer automatically applies these transformations:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Projection pushdown}: \texttt{\$project} early reduces field extraction.
    \item \textbf{Predicate pushdown}: \texttt{\$match} moves as early as possible.
    \item \textbf{Sort elimination}: If data is already sorted by index, skip \texttt{\$sort}.
    \item \textbf{Sequence merging}: Adjacent compatible stages may be merged.
\end{enumerate}

Use \texttt{db.collection.explain("executionStats")} to analyze pipeline performance.

\subsection{Map-Reduce and Alternatives}

MongoDB historically supported Map-Reduce, but it is deprecated in favor of the aggregation pipeline. CouchDB still uses Map-Reduce (JavaScript views) as its primary query mechanism. The Map-Reduce paradigm:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Map}: Emit key-value pairs from each document.
    \item \textbf{Reduce}: Aggregate values for each key.
    \item \textbf{Finalize}: Post-process reduced results.
\end{enumerate}

While powerful, Map-Reduce is harder to optimize and debug than declarative pipelines.

%============================================================================
\section{Indexing Strategies}
%============================================================================

\subsection{The B-Tree Foundation}

Like PostgreSQL and MSSQL, MongoDB uses \textbf{B-Trees} (specifically B+ Trees) for standard indexes. The principles of index selectivity, cardinality, and covering indexes apply identically.

\begin{definition}[B-Tree Index, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
A B-Tree (Balanced Tree) index is a self-balancing tree data structure that maintains sorted data and allows searches, sequential access, insertions, and deletions in logarithmic time $O(\log n)$.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Index Types}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{16_index_types.png}
\caption{MongoDB index types with creation syntax and use cases.}
\label{fig:index-types}
\end{figure}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{2.5cm}p{9.5cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Index Type} & \textbf{Description} \\
\midrule
Single Field & Index on one field. Supports equality and range queries. Can be ascending (1) or descending (-1). \\
Compound & Index on multiple fields. Order matters (left-prefix rule applies). Most important index type. \\
Multikey & Index on array fields. Creates separate index entries for each array element. \\
Text & Inverted index for full-text search across string content. Supports stemming, stop words, relevance scoring. \\
Geospatial & \texttt{2dsphere} (GeoJSON) and \texttt{2d} (legacy coordinate pairs) indexes for location queries. \\
Hashed & Hash of field value. Used for hashed sharding, cannot support range queries. \\
Wildcard & Indexes all fields/subfields matching a pattern (MongoDB 4.2+). Useful for highly dynamic schemas. \\
Clustered & Stores documents directly in index order (MongoDB 5.0+). Eliminates separate collection scan. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsection{The ESR Rule}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{09_esr_rule.png}
\caption{The ESR rule: Equality fields first, Sort fields second, Range fields last.}
\label{fig:esr}
\end{figure}

For compound indexes in MongoDB, the \textbf{Equality, Sort, Range} rule optimizes performance:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Equality} fields first (exact matches, \texttt{\$eq}, \texttt{\$in} with few values).
    \item \textbf{Sort} fields second (ordering, \texttt{sort()}).
    \item \textbf{Range} fields last (inequalities, \texttt{\$gt}, \texttt{\$lt}, \texttt{\$in} with many values).
\end{enumerate}

\begin{keyinsight}
Consider the query: \texttt{db.users.find(\{city: "NYC", age: \{\$gt: 21\}\}).sort(\{name: 1\})}

The optimal index is: \texttt{\{city: 1, name: 1, age: 1\}}

\textbf{Why?} \texttt{city} is equality, \texttt{name} is sort, \texttt{age} is range. If we put \texttt{age} before \texttt{name}, MongoDB cannot use the index for sorting---it must perform an in-memory sort or a collection scan.
\end{keyinsight}

\subsection{Index Intersection}

MongoDB can use multiple indexes to fulfill a query (index intersection), but it is generally less efficient than a single compound index---similar to RDBMS behavior. Index intersection is a fallback, not a strategy.

\subsection{Covered Queries}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{19_covered_query.png}
\caption{A covered query: all fields are satisfied from the index alone. No document fetch is needed.}
\label{fig:covered}
\end{figure}

A query is \textbf{covered} when all fields in the query predicate and projection are contained in the index. MongoDB can then satisfy the query entirely from the index without fetching documents (an ``index-only scan''), analogous to PostgreSQL's \texttt{Index Only Scan}.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
// Index: { city: 1, name: 1 }
// Covered query - only city and name are accessed
db.users.find({ city: "NYC" }, { name: 1, _id: 0 })

// NOT covered - email is not in the index
db.users.find({ city: "NYC" }, { email: 1, _id: 0 })
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Index Build Strategies}

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Foreground}: Blocks all operations on the collection. Fastest but disruptive.
    \item \textbf{Background}: Allows reads/writes during build. Slower, may produce suboptimal index.
    \item \textbf{Hybrid} (MongoDB 4.2+): Combines foreground speed with background availability. Default behavior.
\end{itemize}

\begin{warning}
Building an index on a large collection in production without \texttt{background: true} (on older MongoDB versions) can cause hours of downtime. Always test index builds in staging.
\end{warning}

%============================================================================
\section{Consistency, Transactions, and ACID}
%============================================================================

\subsection{The BASE Paradigm}

Document databases historically prioritized availability over consistency:

\begin{definition}
\textbf{BASE} stands for:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Basically Available}: The system guarantees availability.
    \item \textbf{Soft state}: State may change over time without input (eventual consistency).
    \item \textbf{Eventually consistent}: If no new updates are made, reads will eventually reflect the latest write.
\end{itemize}
BASE is the conceptual opposite of ACID, accepting temporary inconsistency for higher availability.
\end{definition}

\subsection{MongoDB's Multi-Document ACID Transactions}

Since MongoDB 4.0 (replica sets) and 4.2 (sharded clusters), multi-document ACID transactions are supported:

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Atomicity}: All operations in a transaction commit or abort together.
    \item \textbf{Consistency}: Constraints and rules are maintained (though document DBs have fewer declarative constraints than RDBMS).
    \item \textbf{Isolation}: Snapshot isolation (reads see a consistent snapshot from transaction start, not from the beginning of each statement).
    \item \textbf{Durability}: Journaled writes ensure persistence.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{18_transaction_flow.png}
\caption{Multi-document transaction flow: all operations succeed (commit) or all fail (abort).}
\label{fig:transaction}
\end{figure}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, caption={Multi-Document Transaction}, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
const session = db.getMongo().startSession();
session.startTransaction();
try {
    const accounts = session.getDatabase("bank").accounts;
    accounts.updateOne(
        { _id: "alice" },
        { $inc: { balance: -100 } }
    );
    accounts.updateOne(
        { _id: "bob" },
        { $inc: { balance: 100 } }
    );
    session.commitTransaction();
} catch (error) {
    session.abortTransaction();
    throw error;
} finally {
    session.endSession();
}
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{rdbmsnote}
While transactions exist, they carry performance overhead in distributed document databases. The design philosophy remains: \textbf{model your data so that related data lives in a single document}, making atomic single-document updates sufficient for most operations. Transactions are a safety net, not the primary design pattern.
\end{rdbmsnote}

\subsection{Read Concerns and Write Concerns}

MongoDB allows tuning consistency per operation:

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{10_write_concern.png}
\caption{Write concern levels control how many nodes must acknowledge a write before returning to the client.}
\label{fig:write-concern}
\end{figure}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Write Concern} & \textbf{Behavior} & \textbf{Latency/Durability} \\
\midrule
\texttt{\{w: 0\}} & Fire-and-forget (unacknowledged) & Fastest, no durability guarantee \\
\texttt{\{w: 1\}} & Acknowledged by primary & Default, safe on single node \\
\texttt{\{w: "majority"\}} & Committed to majority of nodes & Strong durability, higher latency \\
\texttt{\{j: true\}} & Journaled to disk & fsync equivalent, highest durability \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{15_read_concern.png}
\caption{Read concern levels control the consistency guarantee for read operations.}
\label{fig:read-concern}
\end{figure}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Read Concern} & \textbf{Behavior} & \textbf{Consistency} \\
\midrule
\texttt{"local"} & Read from local node (may rollback) & Fastest, weakest consistency \\
\texttt{"available"} & Similar to local for sharded clusters & Fast \\
\texttt{"majority"} & Only committed data & Strong consistency \\
\texttt{"snapshot"} & For transactions, consistent snapshot & Serializable view within tx \\
\texttt{"linearizable"} & Linearizable reads (slowest) & Strict consistency \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{keyinsight}
The combination of \texttt{writeConcern: "majority"} and \texttt{readConcern: "majority"} provides \textbf{read-your-own-writes consistency} and \textbf{causal consistency} in MongoDB. This is the sweet spot for most applications that need strong consistency without the latency of linearizable reads.
\end{keyinsight}

%============================================================================
\section{Distributed Architecture}
%============================================================================

\subsection{Replication: Replica Sets}

MongoDB uses \textbf{replica sets} for high availability:

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Primary}: Accepts all write operations. There is exactly one primary at any time.
    \item \textbf{Secondaries}: Replicate the primary's oplog (operation log) asynchronously.
    \item \textbf{Arbiter}: Participates in elections without storing data. Used to break ties in odd-member sets.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{05_replica_set.png}
\caption{MongoDB replica set architecture. The primary accepts writes; secondaries replicate via the oplog.}
\label{fig:replica-set}
\end{figure}

If the primary fails, secondaries hold an election (Raft-like consensus algorithm) to promote a new primary. The election timeout is configurable (default 10 seconds).

\begin{keyinsight}
The \textbf{oplog} (operations log) is a capped collection that records all write operations as idempotent operations. Secondaries tail the oplog to apply changes. This is conceptually similar to PostgreSQL's WAL (Write-Ahead Log) streaming replication, but the oplog is at the \textbf{logical} operation level rather than the physical page level. This means:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Oplog entries are human-readable (mostly).
    \item Cross-version replication is possible (within limits).
    \item The oplog can be used for change streams and point-in-time recovery.
\end{itemize}
\end{keyinsight}

\subsection{Sharding: Horizontal Scaling}

When data exceeds the capacity of a single node, \textbf{sharding} distributes data across multiple servers.

\subsubsection{Sharding Components}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{06_sharding.png}
\caption{Sharded cluster architecture: mongos routers, config servers, and shard replica sets.}
\label{fig:sharding}
\end{figure}

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Shard}: A replica set holding a subset of data.
    \item \textbf{Config Servers}: Store metadata about which chunks live on which shards (the ``catalog'').
    \item \textbf{Mongos Router}: Query router that directs operations to the correct shard(s). Can be horizontally scaled.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Shard Keys}

Choosing a \textbf{shard key} is the most critical design decision in a sharded cluster:

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Cardinality}: High cardinality prevents chunk imbalance. A shard key with low cardinality (e.g., \texttt{country} with 5 values) creates at most 5 chunks.
    \item \textbf{Frequency}: Low-frequency values prevent ``hot shards.'' If 80\% of writes are for \texttt{country: "US"}, the US shard becomes a bottleneck.
    \item \textbf{Monotonicity}: Monotonically increasing keys (e.g., timestamps, ObjectIds, auto-incrementing integers) cause write hotspots on the last chunk.
\end{itemize}

\begin{antipattern}
Using \texttt{\_id} (ObjectId) as a shard key is a common anti-pattern. ObjectIds are monotonically increasing, so all inserts go to the last chunk, creating a write hotspot. Use a hashed shard key on \texttt{\_id} instead: \texttt{sh.shardCollection("db.coll", \{\_id: "hashed"\})}.
\end{antipattern}

\subsubsection{Chunk Splitting and Balancing}

Data is divided into \textbf{chunks} (default max 64MB). The balancer migrates chunks between shards to maintain even distribution. This is analogous to range partitioning in PostgreSQL, but automated and distributed.

\begin{tip}
Pre-split chunks before a bulk load to avoid the balancer fighting with your ingestion. Use \texttt{sh.splitAt()} to define chunk boundaries in advance.
\end{tip}

\subsection{The CAP Theorem Revisited}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{System Configuration} & \textbf{CAP Choice} & \textbf{Notes} \\
\midrule
MongoDB (single node) & CP & Like any single-server RDBMS \\
MongoDB (replica set, default) & AP & Reads from secondaries may be stale \\
MongoDB (majority reads/writes) & CP & Strong consistency, lower availability \\
CouchDB & AP & Multi-version concurrency, conflict resolution \\
DynamoDB & AP (tunable) & Per-operation consistency settings \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

%============================================================================
\section{Major Document Database Implementations}
%============================================================================

\subsection{MongoDB}

The dominant document database. Key features:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item BSON storage, rich query language, aggregation pipeline.
    \item Multi-document ACID transactions (4.0+).
    \item Change streams (reactive programming, event sourcing).
    \item Time-series collections, clustered indexes, columnar compression (5.0+).
    \item Atlas: Managed cloud service with global clusters, auto-scaling, serverless instances.
    \item Realm: Mobile database with sync to MongoDB Atlas.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Amazon DocumentDB}

AWS-managed service with MongoDB compatibility (3.6/4.0/5.0 API). Uses Aurora's distributed storage subsystem rather than MongoDB's storage engine. Good for AWS-native shops that want MongoDB API without operational overhead.

\subsection{Azure Cosmos DB (MongoDB API)}

Microsoft's globally distributed database with multiple API choices (SQL, MongoDB, Cassandra, Gremlin, Table). Offers tunable consistency levels and multi-region writes. The MongoDB API is wire-protocol compatible but has some feature gaps.

\subsection{Couchbase}

Combines document storage with memcached caching. Uses N1QL (SQL-like query language for JSON, pronounced ``nickel''). Strong focus on mobile/edge synchronization (Couchbase Lite) and full-text search.

\subsection{Apache CouchDB}

Apache project emphasizing REST API, eventual consistency, and multi-master replication. Uses Map-Reduce views and Mango queries. Excellent for offline-first applications where devices sync when connectivity returns.

\subsection{Google Firestore}

Google's serverless document database. Real-time synchronization, offline persistence, and hierarchical collections. Optimized for mobile and web applications. Charges per read/write/delete operation.

\subsection{Amazon DynamoDB (with Document Model)}

While primarily a key-value store, DynamoDB supports document-like items (nested maps/lists). Single-table design patterns enable complex access patterns. Extremely low latency at scale.

\subsection{PostgreSQL JSONB}

Not a document database per se, but PostgreSQL's \texttt{JSONB} type allows hybrid relational/document workloads:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Supports JSON indexing (GIN indexes on JSONB).
    \item JSON aggregation functions (\texttt{jsonb\_agg}, \texttt{jsonb\_build\_object}).
    \item SQL/JSON path queries (SQL:2016 standard).
    \item Full ACID transactions across relational and JSONB columns.
\end{itemize}

\begin{rdbmsnote}
If you love PostgreSQL but need document flexibility, \texttt{JSONB} is a powerful middle ground. You get ACID transactions, joins, and relational constraints alongside schema-flexible JSON columns. However, you lose horizontal sharding, flexible replication topologies, and some document-native query features.
\end{rdbmsnote}

%============================================================================
\section{Advanced Topics}
%============================================================================

\subsection{Change Streams and Event Sourcing}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{14_change_streams.png}
\caption{Change streams provide a pub/sub interface to the oplog, enabling reactive architectures.}
\label{fig:change-streams}
\end{figure}

MongoDB change streams provide a pub/sub interface to the oplog:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
const changeStream = db.users.watch();
changeStream.on("change", next => {
    printjson(next);
    // next.operationType: "insert", "update", "delete", "replace"
    // next.fullDocument: the post-change document
    // next.documentKey: the _id of the changed document
    // next.updateDescription: fields changed (for updates)
});
\end{lstlisting}

This enables:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Event-driven architectures}: Trigger downstream services on data changes.
    \item \textbf{Materialized view updates}: Maintain denormalized views in real-time.
    \item \textbf{Cache invalidation}: Invalidate cache entries when source data changes.
    \item \textbf{Audit logging}: Stream all changes to an audit collection or external system.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Schema Validation}

MongoDB supports JSON Schema validation at the collection level:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
db.createCollection("students", {
    validator: {
        $jsonSchema: {
            bsonType: "object",
            required: ["name", "gpa", "email"],
            properties: {
                name: {
                    bsonType: "string",
                    description: "must be a string and is required"
                },
                gpa: {
                    bsonType: "double",
                    minimum: 0,
                    maximum: 4.0,
                    description: "must be between 0 and 4.0"
                },
                email: {
                    bsonType: "string",
                    pattern: "^.+@.+$",
                    description: "must be a valid email"
                }
            }
        }
    },
    validationLevel: "strict",
    validationAction: "error"
})
\end{lstlisting}

This provides a middle ground between schema-less flexibility and RDBMS rigor. Validation levels:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \texttt{strict}: All inserts and updates must pass validation.
    \item \texttt{moderate}: Existing invalid documents are allowed, but new ones must pass.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Full-Text Search}

MongoDB Atlas offers Atlas Search (based on Apache Lucene). Self-managed MongoDB supports text indexes with basic stemming and relevance scoring:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
// Create text index
db.articles.createIndex({ title: "text", content: "text" })

// Search with relevance scoring
db.articles.find(
    { $text: { $search: "machine learning" } },
    { score: { $meta: "textScore" } }
).sort({ score: { $meta: "textScore" } })
\end{lstlisting}

For production full-text search, consider Elasticsearch, OpenSearch, or Atlas Search.

\subsection{Time-Series Collections}

MongoDB 5.0+ optimizes storage for time-series data:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Automatic bucketing of measurements.
    \item Columnar compression for numeric arrays (delta-of-delta encoding).
    \item Reduced index overhead (one index per bucket, not per measurement).
    \item Optimized query performance for time-range scans.
\end{itemize}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1]
db.createCollection("sensor_data", {
    timeseries: {
        timeField: "timestamp",
        metaField: "sensor_metadata",
        granularity: "minutes"
    }
})
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Security Best Practices}

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Authentication}: Enable SCRAM-SHA-256 or x.509 certificate authentication. Never run without auth in production.
    \item \textbf{Authorization}: Use Role-Based Access Control (RBAC). Principle of least privilege.
    \item \textbf{Encryption at Rest}: Use WiredTiger's encryption at rest (enterprise) or OS-level encryption (LUKS, EBS encryption).
    \item \textbf{Encryption in Transit}: Require TLS 1.2+ for all connections.
    \item \textbf{Network Security}: Bind to localhost or private IPs. Use VPC peering for Atlas.
    \item \textbf{Auditing}: Enable audit logs for compliance (enterprise feature).
    \item \textbf{Field-Level Encryption}: Client-side field-level encryption (CSFLE) encrypts sensitive fields before they leave the client.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Backup and Recovery Strategies}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Consistency} & \textbf{Impact} & \textbf{Use Case} \\
\midrule
\texttt{mongodump} & Point-in-time & High (reads oplog) & Small datasets, logical backup \\
Filesystem Snapshot & Crash-consistent & Low (if LVM/EBS) & Large datasets, physical backup \\
Atlas Backups & Continuous & None & Managed service \\
Oplog Replay & Exact & Low & Point-in-time recovery \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

For point-in-time recovery (PITR), combine a base snapshot with oplog replay:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item Take a filesystem snapshot.
    \item Continuously archive the oplog.
    \item To recover to time $T$, restore snapshot + replay oplog up to $T$.
\end{enumerate}

%============================================================================
\section{Use Cases and Anti-Patterns}
%============================================================================

\subsection{Ideal Use Cases}

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Content Management}: Articles, blogs, product catalogs with varying attributes. Schema flexibility handles diverse content types.
    \item \textbf{User Profiles}: Heterogeneous user data, preferences, activity logs. Embedding handles the one-to-few relationship.
    \item \textbf{IoT and Time-Series}: Sensor data with the bucket pattern. High write throughput, time-range queries.
    \item \textbf{Mobile Applications}: Offline-first sync (Couchbase, Firestore). Documents map naturally to mobile app state.
    \item \textbf{Real-Time Analytics}: Aggregation pipelines on event streams. Change streams feed real-time dashboards.
    \item \textbf{E-Commerce}: Product catalogs with dynamic attributes (size, color, specs vary by category). Polymorphic pattern handles product types.
    \item \textbf{Catalogs and Directories}: Hierarchical data (categories, org charts) maps naturally to nested documents.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Anti-Patterns}

\begin{antipattern}
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Massive Arrays}: Unbounded arrays cause document bloat and performance degradation. Use the outlier pattern or bucket pattern.
    \item \textbf{Deep Nesting}: Excessively nested documents (>$\sim$5 levels) complicate querying and indexing. Flatten where possible.
    \item \textbf{Data Duplication Without Bound}: Updating duplicated data across many documents becomes expensive. Use change streams to propagate updates.
    \item \textbf{Missing Indexes}: Collection scans on large datasets are catastrophic. Always analyze query patterns before going to production.
    \item \textbf{Monotonic Shard Keys}: Causes write hotspots. Use hashed shard keys or compound shard keys with high-cardinality prefix.
    \item \textbf{Treating it like a Relational Database}: Excessive normalization and application-level joins defeat the purpose. Embrace embedding.
    \item \textbf{Storing Large Binary Data in Documents}: BSON's 16MB limit makes documents unsuitable for images/videos. Use GridFS or object storage (S3).
\end{enumerate}
\end{antipattern}

%============================================================================
\section{Migration Strategies from RDBMS}
%============================================================================

\subsection{Schema Discovery and Analysis}

Before migrating, analyze existing tables, relationships, and query patterns:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Identify \textbf{master-detail relationships} suitable for embedding (one-to-few, read together).
    \item Identify \textbf{many-to-many relationships} requiring referencing.
    \item Map \textbf{read-heavy vs. write-heavy} access patterns.
    \item Identify \textbf{hot tables} that would benefit from sharding.
    \item Document \textbf{transaction boundaries}---which operations must be atomic?
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Migration Approaches}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{17_strangler_fig.png}
\caption{The Strangler Fig Pattern: gradually replace RDBMS functionality rather than big-bang migration.}
\label{fig:strangler}
\end{figure}

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Big Bang}: Migrate all at once. High risk, requires downtime. Suitable only for small datasets.
    \item \textbf{Incremental}: Migrate entity types one at a time. Dual-write period ensures consistency.
    \item \textbf{Strangler Fig Pattern}: Gradually replace RDBMS functionality. New features use document DB; old features migrate over time. Lowest risk.
    \item \textbf{Polyglot Persistence}: Keep RDBMS for transactional data; use document DB for content/search data. Both systems coexist permanently.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{22_polyglot_persistence.png}
\caption{Polyglot Persistence: using the best database for each workload type.}
\label{fig:polyglot}
\end{figure}

\subsection{ETL Considerations}

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Handle type mismatches (dates, decimals, binary). Map SQL \texttt{DATE} to BSON \texttt{Date}, \texttt{NUMERIC} to \texttt{Decimal128}.
    \item Flatten or nest based on access patterns, not source schema.
    \item Rebuild indexes after bulk load for efficiency.
    \item Validate data integrity post-migration (counts, checksums, spot checks).
    \item Plan for oplog size during migration---large bulk inserts can overflow the oplog if secondaries can't keep up.
\end{itemize}

%============================================================================
\section{Performance Tuning and Operations}
%============================================================================

\subsection{The Explain Plan}

Just as you use \texttt{EXPLAIN ANALYZE} in PostgreSQL, MongoDB provides \texttt{explain()}:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=MongoDB, literate={$}{{\textdollar}}1, literate={$, literate={$}{{\textd}{{\textdollar}}1ollar}}1]
// Get execution stats for a query
db.users.find({ age: { $gt: 21 } }).explain("executionStats")

// Key fields to examine:
// - executionStats.totalDocsExamined (should be close to totalDocsReturned)
// - executionStats.executionStages.stage (COLLSCAN vs IXSCAN vs FETCH)
// - executionStats.executionTimeMillis
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Working Set and Memory}

MongoDB uses the OS filesystem cache (unlike PostgreSQL's shared buffers). The \textbf{working set} is the subset of data and indexes that fit in RAM:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item If working set $<$ RAM: queries are fast (in-memory).
    \item If working set $>$ RAM: page faults occur, performance degrades.
\end{itemize}

Monitor page fault rates via \texttt{db.serverStatus().extra\_info.page\_faults}.

\subsection{Connection Pooling}

MongoDB drivers maintain connection pools. Key settings:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item \texttt{maxPoolSize}: Maximum connections per application instance (default 100).
    \item \texttt{minPoolSize}: Minimum connections to maintain.
    \item \texttt{maxIdleTimeMS}: Close idle connections after this time.
\end{itemize}

\begin{warning}
Creating a new connection per request is catastrophic for performance. Always reuse connections via the driver's connection pool. In serverless environments (AWS Lambda), use connection caching or MongoDB's serverless instances.
\end{warning}

\subsection{Monitoring and Alerting}

Key metrics to monitor:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Tool} & \textbf{Threshold} \\
\midrule
Replication lag & \texttt{rs.printSecondaryReplicationInfo()} & $<$ 10 seconds \\
Opcounters & \texttt{db.serverStatus().opcounters} & Baseline + 20\% \\
Memory usage & \texttt{db.serverStatus().mem} & $<$ 80\% RAM \\
Connections & \texttt{db.serverStatus().connections} & $<$ 80\% max \\
Slow queries & Profiler / Atlas & $>$ 100ms \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

%============================================================================
\section{Decision Framework}
%============================================================================

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{23_decision_tree.png}
\caption{Decision tree for choosing a document database vs. RDBMS.}
\label{fig:decision}
\end{figure}

\subsection{When to Choose Document}

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Schema flexibility is a core requirement.
    \item Data is hierarchical and read together.
    \item Horizontal scaling is anticipated.
    \item Developer productivity (no ORM) is prioritized.
    \item Rapid iteration and agile development.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{When to Stick with RDBMS}

\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Complex multi-table transactions are the norm.
    \item Strict referential integrity is required.
    \item Complex reporting with many JOINs.
    \item Team expertise is deeply relational.
    \item Existing ecosystem (triggers, stored procedures, views) is extensive.
\end{itemize}

%============================================================================
\section{Summary and Mental Model}
%============================================================================

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{25_concept_map.png}
\caption{Complete concept map of document database topics covered in this guide.}
\label{fig:concept-map}
\end{figure}

\begin{keyinsight}
\textbf{Your new mental model:}
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Documents are atomic units of consistency}. Design around them.
    \item \textbf{Embedding is the default}; referencing is the exception.
    \item \textbf{Query patterns drive data model}, not the other way around.
    \item \textbf{Indexes are not automatic}; you must design them like in RDBMS.
    \item \textbf{Distributed by design}; think about replication and sharding early.
    \item \textbf{Schema flexibility is a feature, not an excuse for chaos}. Use validation.
    \item \textbf{Consistency is tunable}; understand readConcern and writeConcern.
    \item \textbf{BSON is not JSON}; it adds types and performance optimizations.
\end{enumerate}
\end{keyinsight}

\vspace{1cm}
\noindent\rule{\textwidth}{0.4pt}
\begin{center}
\textit{``The question is not whether document databases are better than relational databases.\\The question is which data model best fits your access patterns, consistency requirements,\\and operational constraints.''}
\end{center}

%============================================================================
\section{Exercises}
%============================================================================

\begin{exercise}
\textbf{Exercise 1: Data Modeling}

You are designing a database for a university course registration system. Each course has:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Basic info: title, code, credits, description
    \item One instructor (name, email, department)
    \item Many students (name, email, major, enrollment date)
    \item Many sessions (date, time, room, topic)
    \item Prerequisites (list of course codes)
\end{itemize}

Model this in MongoDB. Decide which data to embed and which to reference. Justify your decisions using the embedding vs. referencing criteria.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
\textbf{Exercise 2: Aggregation Pipeline}

Given an \texttt{orders} collection with fields \texttt{\_id}, \texttt{customerId}, \texttt{items} (array of \texttt{\{productId, quantity, price\}}), \texttt{orderDate}, and \texttt{status}, write an aggregation pipeline that:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item Filters for completed orders in 2024.
    \item Calculates total revenue per customer.
    \item Joins with a \texttt{customers} collection to get customer names.
    \item Returns top 10 customers by revenue.
\end{enumerate}
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
\textbf{Exercise 3: Index Design}

For the query:
\begin{verbatim}
db.products.find({ category: "electronics", price: { $lt: 500 } })
      .sort({ rating: -1 })
\end{verbatim}

Design the optimal compound index using the ESR rule. Explain why your index is optimal and what would happen with a suboptimal index.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
\textbf{Exercise 4: Consistency Analysis}

A financial application requires that when Alice transfers money to Bob:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item The transfer is recorded atomically.
    \item Both account balances are updated together.
    \item No other transaction sees intermediate states.
\end{enumerate}

What readConcern and writeConcern settings would you use? Would you use a multi-document transaction? What are the performance implications?
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
\textbf{Exercise 5: Sharding Design}

A social media application has a \texttt{posts} collection with 10 billion documents. The access pattern is:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item 90\% of reads are for posts from the last 24 hours.
    \item 70\% of writes are new posts.
    \item Users frequently query posts by \texttt{userId} and \texttt{createdAt}.
\end{itemize}

Design a shard key. Explain your choice and discuss potential pitfalls.
\end{exercise}

\end{document}
